TypeScript style conventions for type safety, imports, and code style.

- Use strict TypeScript settings (enabled in `tsconfig.json`)
- Prefer `type` over `interface` for object types (unless extending)
- Use `as const` for literal types and readonly arrays
- Avoid `any` at all costs - use `unknown` if type is truly unknown
- Import types with `import type` syntax: `import type { Tables, TablesInsert } from '@/types/database-generated.types'`
- Use path aliases when importing from `src/` directory: `import type { HydratedEntity } from '@/types/hydrated'`
- Use generated types from `database-generated.types.ts`: `Tables<'table_name'>` for row types, `TablesInsert<'table_name'>` for insert types, `TablesUpdate<'table_name'>` for update types
- Import types from `salvageunion-reference` package: Use `SURef*` prefix types (e.g., `SURefChassis`, `SURefEquipment`), use `SURefSchemaName` for schema name unions
- Use meaningful generic names: `T`, `TData`, `TVariables` with constraints when needed: `<T extends { id: string }>`
- Use `Omit`, `Pick`, `Partial`, `Required` from TypeScript, use `type-fest` utilities when needed
- Use Prettier for formatting (run `bun run format` before committing)
- Use ESLint (run `bun run lint` to check)
